data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`** (or `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`, or `Thread.Interrupt`). It only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — all of which work identically in .NET 8. No migration is needed.

That said, the modern idiomatic approach would be to use `Task`-based parallelism:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item)));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

This is optional — your current code will compile and run correctly on .NET 8 as-is.
